Title: Risk Sharing, Measuring Variability, and Distortion Riskmetrics
Author-Name: Jean-Gabriel Lauzier
Author-X-Name-First: Jean-Gabriel
Author-X-Name-Last: Lauzier
Author-Email: jlauzier@mun.ca
Author-Name: Liyuan Lin
Author-X-Name-First: Liyuan Lin
Author-X-Name-Last: Lin
Author-Email: Liyuan.Lin@monash.edu
Author-Name: Ruodu Wang
Author-X-Name-First: Ruodu
Author-X-Name-Last: Wang
Author-Email: wang@uwaterloo.ca
Keywords: Signed Choquet Integrals; Risk Sharing; Inter-Quantile Difference; Variability Measures; Pairwise Counter-Monotonicity
Abstract: We address the problem of sharing risk among agents with preferences modelled by a generalclass 
of comonotonic additive and law-invariant functionals that need not be either monotoneor convex. Such 
functionals are called distortion riskmetrics, which include many statisticalmeasures of risk and variability 
used in portfolio optimization and insurance. The set of Pareto Optimal allocations is characterized under
various settings of general or comonotonic risk sharing problems. We solve explicitly Pareto-optimal allocations 
among agents using the Gini deviation, the mean-median deviation, or the inter-quantile difference as the relevant 
variability measures. The latter is of particular interest, as optimal allocations are not comonotonic in the 
presenceof inter-quantile difference agents; instead, the optimal allocation features a mixture of pairwise 
counter-monotonic structures, showing some patterns of extremal negative dependence.
